observations.recommendation:
We recommended and the Management agreed that the Local Chief Executive:

Require the Municipal Accountant to:

effect necessary adjusting entries in the books of accounts to reclassify the remaining completed infrastructure projects still recorded under the CIP  accounts to the appropriate PPE accounts;

compute the corresponding depreciation expense, prior period adjustments relative there to, and accumulated depreciation for all completed projects as of December 31, 2023;

continue to coordinate with the Municipal Engineer to obtain the status of on-going projects to properly classify the asset accounts as of year-end.

Require the Municipal Engineer to constantly update the Municipal Accountant on the status of accomplishments of on-going agency assets and public infrastructure projects for accurate presentation of related accounts in the financial statements.

We recommended and the Management agreed that:

All Municipal Officials and Employees with unliquidated cash advances shall cause the immediate   liquidation of their cash advances in accordance with the rules and regulations and to observe the prescribed period of liquidation; and

The Municipal Accountant to:

Issue within 10 days before the expiration of the one calendar month period, specified under Section 22 of Executive Order No. 77 for official local travel, a written reminder under signature of the head of agency or his authorized representative, enjoining the official or employee concerned to render an account of the cash advance received for his/her travel, pursuant to the rules and regulations on the liquidation of cash advances;

Issue demand letters to those accountable officers with outstanding cash advances that are already beyond the liquidation period;

Refrain from granting additional cash advance to any official or employee unless the previous cash advance given to him/ her is first settled or a proper accounting thereof is made;

Submit to the Office of the Auditor the DVs, supporting documents, and bank statements of those cash advances that are not liquidated up to this date; and

Determine the dormant accounts and to request for write-off by strictly complying the requirements of COA Circular     No. 2016-005 dated December 19, 2016.

We recommended and the Management agreed to:

Identify impediments and deterrents affecting the implementation of planned PPAs and develop solutions to address such issues;

Ensure that the development projects funded under the 20% Development Fund are well-planned, procurement- and- implementation ready and properly coordinated with the concerned departments; 

Require the Municipal Planning and Development Office to coordinate with the Municipal Engineering Office, and regularly monitor the implementation of the targeted development projects funded out of 20% DF; and

Ensure that the 20% Development Fund is fully utilized in order that the target beneficiaries could timely avail of the benefits and usage of the projects.

We recommended and the Local Chief Executive agreed to direct the:

Municipal Accountant to prepare the Disbursement Voucher for the reversion of the unexpended balance of LDRRMF-STF from CYs 2011 to 2018 amounting to ₱1.868 million to the General Fund;

Municipal Treasurer to issue a check for the transfer of the unexpended balance of LDRRMF-STF from CYs 2011 to 2018 amounting to ₱1.868 million from LDRRMF-STF account to the General Fund account;

Municipal Accountant to prepare Journal Entry Voucher adjusting the balance of the Trust Liability-DRRM account corresponding to the unexpended balance of LDRRMF-STF from CYs 2011 to 2018 amounting to ₱1.868 million transferred to the General Fund;

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive direct the concerned officers and employees to stop the practice of reimbursement or direct purchase of goods and services;


We also recommended that the Local Chief Executive thru the Bids and Awards Committee to strictly adhere to the provisions of RA
No. 9184 and its 2016 Revised IRR in conducting its procurement activities and withhold taxes therefrom, if applicable.

We recommended and the management agreed to: 

Trace/find the original title of lands owned by the Municipality as shown in the tax declaration and file the same;


Direct the Municipal Accountant to recognize in the books of account the unrecorded land properties of the Municipality;

Direct the Municipal Accountant to maintain Property, Plant and Equipment Ledger Cards for the land account; and

Direct the General Services Officer to maintain Property Cards for the parcels of land and other real properties owned by the Municipality.

We recommended and the management agreed to direct the:

GSO Officer to make sure that a pre-numbered Trip-ticket shall be issued every time the vehicle is dispatched;

GSO Designate to submit the Monthly Report of Official Travels and Fuel Consumption;

We recommended that the LCE direct the concerned personnel in-charge of the SWM Program to: 

Require and/or observe the strict implementation of mandatory segregation of solid wastes from source to disposal facility; 


Establish MRF that includes solid waste transfer station or sorting station, drop-off center, composting facility and recycling facility.

We recommended and the Municipal Mayor agreed to:
Require the Municipal Accountant to:
Properly record ongoing projects under Construction in Progress, rather than directly in the PPE accounts;
Make the necessary adjusting entries in the books of accounts to reclassify the remaining completed projects currently recorded under the CIP accounts to the correct PPE accounts;
Compute the corresponding depreciation expense, prior period adjustments relative thereto, and accumulated depreciation for all completed projects;
Coordinate with the Municipal Engineer to obtain updated information on the status of ongoing projects to ensure proper classification of the asset accounts as of year-end; and
Direct the Municipal Engineer to provide the Municipal Accountant with copies of the Report of Completed Projects or Report on Government Projects/ Programs/Activities with necessary supporting documents, to ensure accurate presentation of related accounts in the financial statements.

We recommended, and the Municipal Mayor agreed to direct the Municipal Accountant to:
Correct the misclassification of depreciation for Building and Other Structures;
Recognize and record accumulated depreciation for all existing Property, Plant, and Equipment (PPE) accounts in accordance with IPSAS;
Compute and properly apply the correct recognition of depreciation expense for PPE accounts for the current year; and
Make the necessary prior period adjustments to accurately reflect their balances in the year-end financial statements.

We recommended and the Municipal Mayor agreed to direct the Municipal Treasurer and Municipal Accountant to:
Prioritize the reconciliation of the ₱1.019 million discrepancy by reviewing the accounting records, cashbooks, and supporting documentation from the prior periods to promptly address the unresolved discrepancies;
Make the necessary adjustments to reflect the correct balance of the Cash – Local Treasury account in the Financial Statements;
Ensure strict adherence to the monthly reconciliation of cashbook balances with subsidiary accounting records, in compliance with the principles of faithful representation and fair presentation as stated in IPSAS 1;
Conduct a comprehensive review of all financial transactions for the current year to prevent future discrepancies and improve the credibility of the Municipality’s financial reporting; and
Develop a more stringent records management policy to ensure that all transactions are supported by proper documentation.

We recommended and the Municipal Mayor agreed to direct the Municipal Accountant to:
Ensure strict adherence to COA Circular No. 2012-002 and IPSAS 1, particularly in the proper recording and transfer of unutilized balances, to ensure the fair presentation of Trust Liabilities-DRRM in the financial statements;
Establish a regular monitoring and reconciliation process to track the status of LDRRMF balances and ensure compliance with reversion rules;
Review and make necessary adjustments to transfers of unexpended balances to the Special Trust Fund, particularly ensuring the correct treatment of LDRRMF-CO balances; and
Assess the balances of LDRRMF-MOOE and LDRRMF-30% QRF and prepare the required entries for their reversion to the General Fund.

We recommended and the Municipal Mayor agreed to direct the concerned officials to:
Ensure strict adherence to the prescribed Perpetual Inventory Method in accounting for inventories;
Consistently prepare the Requisition and Issue Slip (RIS) and weekly, submit the Summary of Supplies and Materials Issued (SSMI) and copies of the RIS to the Accounting Office to properly support the recognition of expense;
Conduct regular and complete physical counts of inventory at least twice a year;
Submit the Report of the Physical Count of Inventories (RCPI) to the Audit Team, Accounting Office, and the GSO within the prescribed period;
Maintain and regularly update Supplies Ledger Cards and Stock Cards for each type of supply item to ensure proper tracing and tracking of receipts and issuances of inventories;
Strengthen coordination between the General Services Office (GSO) and the Accounting Office to ensure accuracy and consistency in inventory reporting;
Provide training for key personnel on inventory management and government accounting procedures; and
Develop and enforce more stringent internal control polices for inventories, clearly defining roles, responsibilities timelines and required documentations for procurement, issuance, and reporting of supplies.

We recommended and the Municipal Mayor agreed to direct the Municipal Accountant, Municipal Budget Officer, MEED Designate, and all concerned Officials to:
Set up and maintain a special account in the GF for each LEE;
Ensure that profits or income derived from the operation of LEE are applied to (1) cost of improvement, repair, and related expenses of the LEE, (2) return of advances received by the LEEs to the GF, and (3) any excess shall form part of the GF;
Develop and finalize a comprehensive Business Plan for each LEE covering all relevant facets of the LEE’s operations, including management, operations, staffing, risk analysis, marketing, and sales, to be approved by the Municipal Mayor and submitted to the local Sanggunian;
Assess the financial performance of each LEE and, if financially self-sufficient (i.e., 100 percent cost recovery and/or generating net revenue), follow the processes outlined in Section 7.2 of the LEE Manual; otherwise, comply with the guidelines under Section 7.3 for non-self-sustaining enterprises.

We recommended and the Municipal Mayor agreed to direct the Municipal Treasurer's Office (MTO) to:
Adhere to the posting guidelines outlined for the Notice of Delinquencies and utilize all feasible methods to enhance collection efforts, striving to meet the targets set by the Bureau of Local Government Finance (BLGF);
Revive and expand the "Pulong-pulong" (community tax education) meetings in all barangays to enhance public awareness of tax obligations and encourage timely payments;
Coordinate with the Municipal Assessor’s Office to regularly update and clean the list of Real Property Units (RPUs), including proper documentation for properties affected by disputes, donations, or legal issues; and
Strengthen coordination among the Municipal Treasurer’s Office, the Municipal Assessor’s Office, and the Barangay Treasurers to ensure a more efficient collection process and the accurate reporting of tax delinquencies.

We recommended and the Municipal Mayor agreed to direct the concerned officials to:
Strengthen project planning and prioritization by ensuring that all proposed development projects are well-planned and procurement-ready;
Enhance monitoring and accountability by establishing a project monitoring committee or by fortifying existing mechanisms to regularly track the implementation and utilization of DF projects;
Expedite realignment and fund reprogramming by immediately realigning unutilized balances, especially those from previous years, to fund new or ongoing projects that are more feasible and responsive to current community needs; and
Conduct capacity-building activities by training local project managers and procurement personnel on efficient fund utilization, project implementation timelines, and compliance with DILG-DBM JMC No. 2020-1.

We recommended and the Municipal Mayor agreed to direct the Municipal Treasurer and Municipal Accountant to:
Prioritize the reconciliation of the ₱9.244 million discrepancy by thoroughly reviewing the accounting records, cashbooks, and supporting documentation to identify and promptly resolve variances;
Record the necessary adjustments to reflect the stale check amounting to P5,000.00, thereby ensuring the accurate presentation of Cash in Bank-LCCA account in the Financial Statements;
Conduct a comprehensive review of all financial transactions for the current year to prevent discrepancies in the future and to strengthen the reliability of the Municipality’s financial reporting; and
Establish and enforce robust internal controls for monitoring cash balances, ensuring monthly reconciliation between the General Ledger, Cash BOOK and bank records, and regularly verifying the accuracy of financial data.

We recommended and the Municipal Mayor agreed to direct the Gender and Development Focal Point System (GFPS) and other concerned personnel to:
Prioritize the completion of the three-year GAD Agenda before the end of 2025 to serve as the strategic basis for future GPBs;
Ensure timely submission of GPB and GAD AR in compliance to PCW-DILG-DBM-NEDA JMC No. 2022-01;
Strictly adherence to the requirements outlined in Joint Memorandum Circular 2013-01 dated July 2013, as amended by PCW-DILG-DBM-NEDA JMC No. 2016-01 in planning, implementation, and monitoring of GAD Fund; and
Conduct regular assessments of the GAD programs and activities to ensure they are realistic, feasible, and align with the objectives of promoting gender equality and empowering women.

We recommended and the Management agreed to direct the Municipal Treasurer to:

Prepare RAAF and record all the Accountable Forms in her custody including those which are kept in the vault; 

Make sure that all accountable officers who have the assigned accountable forms will prepare the RAAF;

Include/record the checks and cash tickets in the RAAF of the Accountable Officers and eventually in the CRAAF; and

Prepare the CRAAF in accordance with Section 51 of the Manual on NGAS for LGU, Volume II by recording and consolidating the data in the RAAF of each AO.

